    "excerpt":"                Research Description                              I believe that fostering a dynamic synergy between human and machine intelligence will pave the way for a better world. Envisioning a future where truly understanding the intricate connections between mind, behavior, and brain brings forth highly efficient and responsible AI, this collaboration propels humanity and technology into a shared ascent. It empowers us to authentically deepen our understanding of ourselves and the universe.          First, my research focuses on theoretical algorithm and device design for human-level intelligent machines. These designs are based on insights from neuroscience, psychology, and cognitive science, derived from organisms that have successfully survived with limited resources(e.g. time and energy). Primarily, I am interested in proposing AI models and computing devices based on theoretical breakthroughs such as Active Inference. This exploration seeks to uncover the potential for energy-efficient and fast intelligent algorithms. Furthermore, I am deeply interested in how symbolic systems such as language and mathematics emerge from sub-symbolic systems such as neural networks. This includes proposing responsible language models and discovering new methods to evaluate AI model stability(related post). Lastly, I propose AI models inspired by evolutionary psychology, challenging the traditional Tabula Rasa paradigm and emphasizing the importance of biological complexity in the learning process.      Additionally, I am dedicated to developing a unified framework for the mind-behavior-brain connection. This involves analyzing principles such as the free energy principle, inductive bias principle, and data compression principle. This approach plays a crucial role in incorporating previously unexplained phenomena into the scientific domain. For example, to investigate consciousness, I formalize and compare existing theories like the global neural workspace theory, attention schema theory, and predictive coding theory. Through these comparisons, I propose new theories and plan more extensive research by implementing simulations. Furthermore, to explore hypnosis, I analyze existing theories and drug-based experiments. I also connect theories on the effects and principles of language to propose new theories and develop simulation models, thereby enriching the research.      To achieve these goals, I combine: (1) knowledge from the history of cybernetics and philosophy of mind; (2) mathematical data analysis methods using probabilistic inference and graph theory; (3) modeling with statistical mechanics and complex systems physics; (4) applications of reinforcement learning, world models, and robotics.      In conclusion, my research aims to bridge the gap between theoretical principles and practical applications, providing a comprehensive understanding of complex phenomena and contributing to the advancement of intelligent machine design.   ","url": "http://localhost:4000/research/"
